<subSubSection id="5BCFE39851943753BEE141DCE6AAC016" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="3E35F7FB5CDD1833507FBCEB2D950133" pageNumber="133">Etymology: This species is named for my friend and colleague Dr. Jacques Delabie, for his continuous supply of interesting ants.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="75FF6F7FF8897F5FCD2BBDBD2E8AC344" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2E1A2617E95234509744AAB55F6851AC" pageNumber="133">Comments</paragraph>
<paragraph id="88A982C05C15EC90754FAA6011EDD2A1" lastPageNumber="134" pageNumber="133">
In 
<taxonomicName id="57ADECC9FFE1874F86C53907108F9D4A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:231124" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Monomorium delabiei Fernández" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delabiei">M. delabiei</taxonomicName>
there are two transverse rows of hairs on the clypeus. In the row on the anterior border, the hairs increase in length from the lateral ones towards the midpoint, where they are longest (although not very much longer than the rest); in other words, there is no single medial hair that stands out, a characteristic typical of the tribe. This is also typical of some 
<taxonomicName id="8FC8D17446D416D27B3B909704517374" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24898" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Megalomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Megalomyrmex Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megalomyrmex</taxonomicName>
, and in at least some “ 
<taxonomicName id="42F76656A9D297A7EB1DFA42770BDD95" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2350" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Antichthonidris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Antichthonidris Snelling" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Antichthonidris</taxonomicName>
” workers, there is no apical medial seta. The clypeus forms a medial convexity with only a very weak trace of carinae. The tentorial pit is more than halfway between antennal receptacles and mandibular base (as in some “ 
<taxonomicName id="7A155F14798214F1F4A86C74B64BFEAB" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2350" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Antichthonidris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Antichthonidris Snelling" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Antichthonidris</taxonomicName>
”), rather than near the antennal alveolus (as in some Neotropical 
<taxonomicName id="5A811D6DC587EE671E90031F49CBC100" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24899" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Monomorium Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Monomorium</taxonomicName>
). The form of the propodeal spiracle is somewhat similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="BE2E748E08DC4489E900A5A5EE69838B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24900" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Nothidris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Nothidris Ettershank" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nothidris</taxonomicName>
(Bolton, 1994: 104), with a visible vestibule preceding anteriorly the spiracle proper: in typical 
<taxonomicName id="22DD38C6ECAB2271E8572F8C8217236A" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24899" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Monomorium Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Monomorium</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="25925886A68FF22D3E92791205B78E66" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24898" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Megalomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Megalomyrmex Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="133" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megalomyrmex</taxonomicName>
the spiracle is round and without anterior vestibules. The postpetiole has a robust, pointed ventral tubercle, a characteristic apparently not shared with other members of the genus or with 
<taxonomicName id="81CE59837496DDD6E512235D39A8049B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24898" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Megalomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Megalomyrmex Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megalomyrmex</taxonomicName>
. The absence of the transverse propodeal carina excludes, by definition, the inclusion of this species in the typical 
<taxonomicName id="560F1B373A978B4B62AA27DE1A6FAA16" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24898" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Megalomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Megalomyrmex Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Megalomyrmex</taxonomicName>
, although the character is not universal within the genus, and can be present in some 
<taxonomicName id="A831C5C725E9676341B68A5C8400E0E3" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24899" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Monomorium Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="134" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Monomorium</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
